gomodel:SYNGO_250  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: This publication provides some evidence that PKC lambda/iota regulates the insertion of AMPAR at the PSD.\n-A specific shRNA blocks the induction of LTP in hippocampal slices, which can be rescued by re-expression of PKC-lambda. (Figure 1)\n-PI3K activation increases PKC lambda auto-phosphorylation and EPSC amplitudes. This is inhibited by PKC-lambda shRNA, and an inhibitor (Myr-aPKC-PS, more commonly known as ZIP) with some specificity to PKC-lambda. (Figure 2).\n-PI3K activation leads to increased surface expression of GluRs, which is inhibited by Myr-aPKC-PS (Figure 3C-F).\n-PI3K activation leads to increased mEPSC amplitudes, which can be blocked by PKC-lambda shRNA and Myr-aPKC-PS (Figure 3G-H).\n\nIt should be noted that at the concentration used, Myr-aPKC-PS also strongly inhibits PKC-zeta (see Figure 1D and Tsokas et al 2016). Thus, in several assays in this publication, it cannot be excluded that observed effects are mediated by PKC-zeta. The role of PKC-lambda in LTP is debated and likely involves an interplay with PKC-zeta expression (Tsokas et al 2016).. Experimental description: Male Sprague Dawley rats, 2-3 weeks old, were anaesthetized with ethyl ether and decapitated.\n\nThe species of the PKClambda overexpression construct is traced back to *rat* via accession NM_022507.1 (supplemental information)" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7620-2704" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1558-1958" ;
        dc:date           "2017-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_250" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

